I’ve seen one OA thread discussing energy chain solutions, particularly saying that they were going to use a setup similar to 2910 in 2023 via CF springs in order to keep the chain in tension.

My question is whether it is really necessary to have some sort of tensioning system like this, and if so, can you give any examples?

Also, what recommendations would you give to a team using energy chains for the first time?

I’m assuming you are referencing this post from our build blog (quoted for context)

WildStang Robotics Program: Team 111 and 112 Build Blog - 2025

111 E Chain Breaking

Obviously in that case, it is going to be necessary to have some method of controlling the e chain so it doesn’t get caught under the lift again. However, that is also a two-stage lift with around 6 feet of travel, with an exceptionally long e chain to match. For contrast, 112 is building a single stage lift with about 30" of travel; at this point I don’t expect to need a spring to manage the cable as there is much less length to swing around and get caught under the lift, but we will of course add one if it becomes an issue during testing. Compare also 2910 from 2023: their travel was probably closer to 30", but the arm rotated so gravity wasn’t necessarily always in the right orientation to keep the extra length of the chain in the right position.
